post_text:
9.11.20
Dear Greensburg SalemSchool District Families,
The U.S. Secretary of Agriculture recently announced that the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) will extend several flexibilities for school meals throughout the remainder of 2020. The USDA stated, “As our nation reopens and people return to work, it remains critical our children continue to receive safe, healthy, and nutritious food.”

At this time the free meals for all students will only run until December 31, 2020 or until funding is no longer available at which time statuses will return to Paid, Free and Reduced rates based on qualifications and applications, so please continue to return free and reduced meal applications as soon as possible to avoid any gap in benefits.

We remain committed to providing students access to healthy, nutritious and wholesome meals while assuring the utmost food safety without compromising quality.

Thank you!
Scott Hudak
Regional Chef
Greensburg Salem Food Service Director

post_text:
Dear Greensburg Salem Families,

This week, U.S. Secretary of Agriculture Sonny Perdue announced that the U.S. Department of Agriculture (USDA) will extend several flexibilities for school meals until as late as December 31, 2020. The flexibilities allow school districts to continue serving free meals to all children/students into the Fall months. "As our Nation reopens and people return to work, it remains critical our children continue to receive safe, healthy and nutritious food" the USDA said.

All Greensburg Salem students will be eligible for free meals whether they are learning in the classroom or virtually through the Fall. In addition, families with children who are not yet school age are also eligible for meals under this program.

post_text:
Dear Kindergarten Parents,

With the disruption of the supply of laptops and computer tablets, we had to alter our plan for instruction for kindergarten. We will now be providing half day kindergarten for the students at each elementary school. We will be dividing the kindergarten students into smaller groups to maintain social distancing guidelines and will be providing half day classes on Mondays, Tuesdays, Thursdays and Fridays for the first semester. The students will be going to either morning or afternoon sessions on those days. Students will be bused to and from school. The morning session runs from 9:00-11:30 AM and PM is 1:00-3:30 The PM arrival is at 12:50 PM. Bus schedules will be accessible through the parent portal. Please contact your child's individual principal for information about student class groupings.

post_text:
Dear Students and Parents,

We were notified this afternoon at 3:22 by CCL Pro-Tech that the HP Stream Laptop delivery date from the supplier has been pushed back again to Friday, October 9th. The affects students in grades two through seven. Classes will still resume on Tuesday, September 8th for students in the A and the B groups in the blended setting, as well as remote learners. Faculty and staff will work to provide traditional paper assignments, projects and assessments that students will work on the days that they are learning at home and bring with them on the days they are in the buildings in class. We regret the delay and inconvenience this may cause.

Sincerely,

Dr. Peiffer

post_text:
Dear Parents and Students,

Due to a delay from the manufacturer in the provision and shipment of the HP laptop streams, we will not be able to distribute these devices to students as originally planned. These devices are now expected to arrive after August 22nd and they will need to be prepped before they can be distributed. As a result, Greensburg Salem will not be able to open school on August 26th as originally planned. Instead, we will begin the school year on Tuesday, September 8th after Labor Day. A revised school calendar will be forthcoming. We apologize for any inconvenience this may cause.

post_text:
Dear Greensburg Salem:

If you or child is interested in cyber learning, look no further than the Greensburg Salem remote learning and ePride cyber programs. Since 2012, Greensburg Salem has successfully worked with over 600 students and families to provide flexible and rigorous learning in the virtual environment. As a Greensburg Salem remote learner, you will earn a Greensburg Salem diploma, have access to all programs, extra-curricular activities, facilities, advanced placement courses, guidance and career planning, and all other amenities provided to every Greensburg Salem student. To enroll or learn more, email ePride@gslions.net or call your building’s main office.

post_text:
CHEERLEADING TRYOUTS 2020-2021

>>> It’s time for tryouts to begin our new cheer season! We know things are uneasy right now, and we are already behind schedule for the new season. In light of the current social situation we will be doing things differently this year. If you are interested in trying out for the 20-21 school year (9th-12th grade) please contact Linda Carpellotti (duxburyl@icloud.com) or Linda OBryan (Linda.obryan@yahoo.com)to sign up and receive your packet by July 1st. Please make sure that you put in the subject line Cheer Tryout. We will forward the tryout packet to be completed and must be emailed back to us by July 11th . DO NOT RETURN PACKETS TO ATHLETIC OFFICE. We will have tryout practices July 27-28-29 5-7 pm High School Auditorium and Tryout on July 31st 10 am-2pm. Tryout times will be assigned. You’re Physicals, Family ID and COVID waiver must be completed and submitted to the Athletic office prior to tryout date (July 31st) or you will not be permitted to tryout. Thank you for your patience during this time.

These students deserve an audience for their hard work. Thank you. Here is the YouTube link if you wish to share it through other social media. https://youtu.be/6JpGP4408tQ

For those of you who have not heard yet, Ty Hutchinson who is in 5th grade at Metzgar, was diagnosed with T-Cell Leukemia this past week. His mom, Mrs. Katie Hutchinson, is the Title I reading teacher at Metzgar.

Ty is currently at Children's Hospital, and once he is discharged, Ty and Mrs. Hutchinson will be traveling weekly to Children's Hospital to continue treatments. Please keep them in your thoughts and prayers as they begin this journey!

Visit https://www.facebook.com/groups/2588049081409732/ for updates and more info about a Go Fund Me to support the family.

Bedford, Blair, Cambria, Fayette, Fulton, Huntingdon, Somerset, and Westmoreland is coordinating a Broadband Survey to assess your current broadband service and needs.

Below you will find the links for both the residential and business broadband surveys. Please help by completing the applicable surveys. This survey is important to all students, to congregate settings like nursing homes, religious groups, schools, etc. We are all impacted by the results, and too few respondents will mean much less financial support for our area.

Residential: https://tinyurl.com/BroadbandHOME

Business: https://tinyurl.com/BroadbandBiz

post_text:
Mrs. Lauren Brown is a PCA at Hutchinson and the mother of Benjamin Brown. Benjamin is in Mrs. Menz's third grade classroom and has been diagnosed with Autism. This year, Mrs. Brown and Mrs. Menz worked together to plan morning meetings, mini lessons, and bulletin board displays to raise Autism Awareness. Sadly, those plans couldn't be carried out due to the school closure. However, Ben's family, friends, classmates, and Hutchinson staff have worked together to "LIGHT IT UP BLUE" in many different ways. We love and support him and all others living with Autism. We believe that our differences make us unique and beautiful! April is Autism Awareness Month. Learn more about how you can show YOUR support at

https://www.autism-society.org/get-involved/national-autism-awareness-month/.

post_text:
Good evening Greensburg Salem families. Although the District initially planned to offer assignments for students to complete at home, we recently received guidance from the United States Department of Education and the Pennsylvania Department of Education advising us against delivering instruction during the closure.

Therefore, teachers will not be providing assignments, feedback on assignments, or assessments online at this time. However we encourage parents to work with their children at home to read and seek out online resources to keep their children engaged with learning.

Teachers may also share practice items on their website or through other digital resources to help students stay sharp. In addition, if students have previously assigned work that they have not yet completed, they may complete and submit that work to their teachers electronically or be prepared to submit it upon their return.

Thank you for your patience during these unique times and we will continue to update you as information becomes available to us.

post_text:
Greensburg Salem High School participated in Companies in the Classroom today. Companies in the Classroom is an opportunity for representatives from local businesses and post-secondary education institutions to visit secondary classrooms to learn more about students' educational experiences and the opportunities that are available to them.

The visitors were able to see how GS is preparing our students for the future as they observed lessons and activities in classes today. The representatives also shared information with staff and students about career opportunities and what they look for in an applicant when hiring. Thanks to: Scott DeVinney from Kennametal, Scott Rudy from Elliott, Renee Starek from Seton Hill and Bryon Kohut from WCCC for joining us today.

post_text: The following students: Becky Handke, Alex Wigle, Sean Galvin, Kiera Flanigan, and Alli Jobe presented their idea about sustainable living to professionals at the Covestro headquarters in Pittsburgh. Greensburg Salem was one of many schools that presented their ideas focused around the UN's Sustainable Development Goals. Their idea, entitled "School Garden - Farm to Table" aims to use cafeteria waste to produce compost. This compost will be used grow vegetables and other food that can be used in the school's food classes and dinner programs.

The entire Greensburg Salem community is invited to join us for a night of fun as 10 seniors vie for the title of Mr. GS. Our show will open with a themed introduction video and group dance before the contestants compete in Date Wear, Talent, Formal Wear, and Q & A.

Be sure to vote for the fan favorite award during intermission (additional votes may be purchased). At the end of the night we will announce the Fan Favorite, Mr. Congeniality, and crown Mr. GS 2020!

Mr. GS will be held on Thursday, March 12th at 7:30 pm in the Greensburg Salem High School auditorium. Tickets are $5.00 and can be purchased at the door. Doors open at 7:00 pm.

post_text: Greensburg Salem High School cast of "Phantom of the Opera" had a wonderful surprise before dress rehearsal on Thursday. Mr. James Baker, GSHS Musical Technical Director, arranged a live Facetime interview with Bradley Dean (Monsieur Andre') in the Broadway Production of "Phantom" at the Majestic Theatre in New York City. Mr. Dean gave the students a look at the theatre from the stage and answered questions about the show and musical theatre. Students also had the opportunity to meet Eryn LeCroy (Christine Daae') and Carlton Moe (Ubaldo Piangi). Memories that will last a lifetime!

post_text:
7 students voluntarily joined Mrs. Redinger last evening to observe Dr. Bisignani (Excela Health Orthopedic Surgeon) reconstruct an ACL tear in St. Vincent College’s Human Anatomy Lab. Mrs. Redinger participated, hands-on, in the surgical room for her own professional development to gain further knowledge for orthopedics in her classroom. GS students observed from above and interacted with the surgical team. Pictured below are Regan Lennert, Kegan Murtha,
Dr. Bisignani, Aleah Collins and Christian Hostetler. Not pictured are Adam Nichols, Rachel Leo, and Tori Sarver.

post_text: One of Mrs. Menz’s ELA small groups read about a school in Guatemala that was built by its students out of ecobricks. They did this to solve two problems: an abundance of trash and a lack of money to finish the school. Her student Ryann Foley went home and made an ecobrick of her own. What a great demonstration of her interest and enthusiasm for learning!

post_text: Congratulations to Greensburg Salem Senior DJ Trout and a teammate Robby Hoey from Norwin took first place again at the second round of the Greater Pittsburgh Auto Dealer’s Association’s Annual Joint Automotive Competition at CCAC. DJ and Robby were assigned a 2018 GMAC Acadia for the competition. For their triumph, each student received a Snap-On tool and a $10,000 scholarship to an automotive school of their choice. They will compete next at Nationals in New York City!

post_text: The GSHS eSports Club hosted a Super Smash Bros. tournament on Friday night in the high school library. Congratulations to Luke Cross, who won the event! Money raised at the tournament will be used to buy computer equipment for eSports competitions. The GSHS eSports club is a new organization and competes against other students across the country as part of the North American Scholastic Esports Federation.

post_text:
Dear Parents and students-
After School today around 3:30 at the Middle School, it was reported that a graffiti threat was found in the second floor boys bathroom. The City of Greensburg Police were called and consulted. We do not believe the threat is credible. For the safety of the students and staff, a dog was brought to the school to perform a sweep of the building. In addition to the dog and the K9 officer, two Greensburg Police officers performed the sweep with Mr. Jones later that afternoon. Nothing was found. School will open on time tomorrow and will operate under normal conditions. A Greensburg Police Officer and Officer Grabiak will be at the Middle School as an additional safety precaution.

shared_text:
Greensburg Volunteer Fire Department
December 5, 2019 at 7:21 PM ·

Let’s provide some Christmas Miracles!🥰
We are so very fortunate to have a home to live in and food on the table. Unfortunately, there are many people in our community who struggle to provide a meal for their family. This Christmas the GVFD will be donating meals to some of Greensburg’s less fortunate.
All of these families have children. Let’s make sure these kids don’t go hungry on Christmas. If you are able to sponsor a family for $25 please comment “I’m in” and include your email for invoicing. All orders must be in by December 19th! Let’s do this Greensburg!💝
